  <div class="views-field-title">
                <span class="field-content"><a href="../library/chinafaqs-china-adopts-world-class-pollutant-emissions-standards-coal-power-plants">ChinaFAQs: China Adopts World-Class Pollutant Emissions Standards for Coal Power Plants</a></span>
  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-field-image-fid">
                <span class="field-content"><img src="../files/chinainfo/imagecache/news-image/AirQuality_thumb.jpg" alt="" title="" width="93" height="120" class="imagecache imagecache-news-image imagecache-default imagecache-news-image_default"/></span>
  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-field-library-file-fid">
                <div class="field-content"><div class="filefield-file"><img class="filefield-icon field-icon-application-pdf"  alt="application/pdf icon" src="../sites/all/modules/filefield/icons/application-pdf.png" /><a href="../files/chinainfo/China&#32;FAQs&#32;Emission&#32;Standards&#32;v1.4_0.pdf" type="application/pdf; length=256708">China FAQs Emission Standards v1.4.pdf</a></div></div>
  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-teaser">
                <div class="field-content"><p><b>Key Points</b></p>

<blockquote><blockquote>
<ul><li>China‚Äôs new emissions standards for power plants are comparable to standards in the  developed world in important respects.</li>
<li>These standards are being phased in quickly. They apply to new plants starting Jan. 1, 2012, and existing plants have just 2¬Ω years to meet the standards.</li>
<li>The standards include provisions for even greater stringency in highly polluted areas.</li>
<li>China has raised electricity rates to fund the $41 billion investment in new pollution abatement equipment as well as the operating costs needed to comply with the standards.</li>
<li>These measures also encourage greater energy efficiency and the use of renewables, as they raise the cost of coal-fired power.</li></ul>
</blockquote></blockquote></div>
  </div>
  </div>
